\f0\fs24 \cf0 Anterior shift of the head is generally caused by a pattern of hypertonic upper trapezius and SCM muscles with weakness in the deep neck flexors of the neck.  This is caused by supporting the shoulder blades with the upper trapezius and thus "hanging" the arms from the neck rather than supporting them from the mid back.  To break this pattern exercises should be initiated that stretch the scalenes, upper trapezius and SCM muscles while strengthening the deep neck flexors along with the middle and lower trapezius muscles.}